THE RAPE OF THE SABINE WOMEN (L, 4.)

THE Roman state had now attained such a degree of power that it was a match in arms for any of the neighboring nations; but from the small number of its women, its greatness was not likely to last longer than one age of man, as they had neither hopes of offspring among themselves nor had yet contracted any inter- marriages with their neighbors.
